{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is at real `git` rename detection + CLI parsing/categorization handoff. A unit test on parser fixtures can miss real subprocess output formats and rename-detection behavior. REAL-INFRA is required (real repo + real git subprocess). Rejected lower level: behavior text ties correctness to repository analysis output, not just one local parsing function.","test_description":"Create a temporary real git repo, commit a file, rename it, run the CLI against that repo, and assert report shows 1 rename and 0 add/delete for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This commonly fails at real subprocess/output-decoding boundaries when `git` reports binary diffs. Mocked text fixtures can hide encoding/exit-code/output-shape issues. REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE both point to System.","test_description":"In a temp real git repo, add/modify a binary file (e.g., random bytes), run the CLI, assert process exits successfully and binary file is included in counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Unborn-HEAD behavior is produced by real git repository state and subprocess return behavior. Stubbing can simulate it, but real failures often come from actual git error modes and messages. REJECTION-GATE: Integration rejected because behavior explicitly depends on repository state with no commits.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits, run the CLI, assert successful exit and an empty structured report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.24,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This validates end-to-end correctness against real git history semantics, requiring real filesystem state + real git subprocess results. Integration fakes risk passing while diverging from true git behavior.","test_description":"Build a temp repo with a scripted sequence of add/modify/rename/delete commits, run the CLI over the target range, and assert category counts equal the known ground truth from that sequence.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Staged vs unstaged semantics are git index/worktree behaviors that only reliably appear with real repo state and git plumbing. MOCK-HIDE applies: in-process fakes can trivially make both paths equal and miss real divergence.","test_description":"In a temp repo, create equivalent file changes once as unstaged and once staged, run CLI in each state, and assert byte-identical structured output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
